# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: metabolic-engineering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Fermentation is important in several areas of human society.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Humans have used fermentation in the production and preservation of food for 13,000 years.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] It has been associated with health benefits, unique flavor profiles, and making products have better texture.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Humans and their livestock also benefit from fermentation from the microbes in the gut that release end products that are subsequently used by the host for energy.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Perhaps the most commonly known use for fermentation is at an industrial level to produce commodity chemicals, such as ethanol and lactate.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Ethanol is used in a variety of alcoholic beverages (beers, wine, and spirits) while lactate can be neutralized to lactic acid and be used for food preservation, as a curing agent, or as a flavoring agent.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] This complex metabolism utilizes a wide variety of substrates and can form nearly 300 different combinations of end products.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Fermentation occurs in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The discovery of new end products and new fermentative organisms suggests that fermentation is more diverse than what has been studied.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] However, this definition does not encompass all forms of fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] For example, propionate fermentation which uses H2 as an electron donor, or the second step of butyrate fermentation where CO2 can act as an electron acceptor.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Thus, it is simplest to use this definition while acknowledging that protons can also be used as electron donors and CO2 as acceptors.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In 1876, before the discovery of anaerobic respiration, Louis Pasteur described it as "la vie sans air" (life without air).
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] It was also common for fermentation to be defined based on how fermentation forms ATP which was catabolism that forms ATP through only substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Industrial fermentation is another type of fermentation that is defined loosely as a large-scale biological manufacturing process; however, this definition focuses on the process of manufacturing rather than metabolic details.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Fermentation can be used by organisms to generate a net gain of ATP from exogenous sources of organic molecules, such as glucose.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] It was not a net source of energy in the earliest forms of life because they were mostly single cell organisms living in the ocean and the ocean does not contain significant concentrations of complex organic molecules.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Because fermentation does not need an exogenous electron acceptor, it is able to occur regardless of the environmental conditions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] However, the primary disadvantage of fermentation is that fermentation is relatively inefficient and produces between 2 and 5 ATP molecules per glucose versus 32 ATP molecules during aerobic respiration.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Over 25% of bacteria and archaea carry out fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Fermentation is especially prevalent in prokaryotes of the phylum Bacillota, but is most rare in Actinomycetota, according to phylogenetic analysis.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The fermenting microbes are most frequently found in host-associated habitats such as the gastrointestinal tract, but also sediments, food, and other habitats.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Both bacteria and archaea share the capacity for fermentation, leading to a wide variety of organic end products.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The most common fermentation products include lactate, acetate, ethanol, carbon dioxide (CO2), succinate, hydrogen (H2), propionate, and butyrate.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In humans, fermentation pathways occur in health, as in exercising, and in disease, as in sepsis and hemorrhagic shock, providing energy for a period ranging from 10 seconds to 2 minutes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] During this time, it can augment the energy produced by aerobic metabolism, but is limited by the buildup of lactate.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Like many biochemical reactions, fermentation is an enzyme catalyzed reaction with the goal of either changing the initial substrate or forming a useful byproduct.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] When naturally occurring fermentation is carried out by microbes, the goal is usually to obtain useful metabolic products such as ATP, pyruvate, or lactic acid.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The substrates used in this type of fermentation are often simple sugars (carbohydrates) that serve as a carbon source and this type of fermentation can be carried out by microbes and humans.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Food as a substrate for fermentation is the most common and oldest anthropogenic use of fermentation as it was a method to preserve food.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] This includes cereal, dairy products, rice, honey, bread, and beers.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] This type of naturally occurring fermentation continues to be harnessed by humans for preservative effects, flavor profiles, and texture profiles.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Advances in fermentation has led to the engineering and industrialization of specific microbes and substrates in order to obtain certain flavor and texture profiles – this is most obvious when observing beer fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] When an organic compound is fermented, it is broken down to a simpler molecule and releases electrons.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The electrons are transferred to a redox cofactor, which, in turn, transfers them to an organic compound.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] ATP is generated in the process, and it can be formed via substrate-level phosphorylation or by ATP synthase.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] When glucose is fermented, it enters glycolysis or the pentose phosphate pathway and is converted to pyruvate.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] From pyruvate, pathways branch out to form a number of end products (e.g. lactate).
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] At several points, electrons are released and accepted by redox cofactors (NAD and ferredoxin).
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] At later points, these cofactors donate electrons to their final acceptor and become oxidized.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] ATP is also formed at several points in the pathway.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Yeast and other anaerobic microorganisms can convert the pyruvate produced from the oxidation of glucose by a glycolysis pathway to ethanol and CO2.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In ethanol fermentation, one glucose molecule is converted into two ethanol molecules and two carbon dioxide (CO2) molecules.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] It is used to make bread dough rise: the carbon dioxide forms bubbles, expanding the dough into a foam.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The ethanol is the intoxicating agent in alcoholic beverages such as wine, beer and liquor.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Fermentation of feedstocks, including sugarcane, maize, and sugar beets, produces ethanol that is added to gasoline.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In some species of fish, such as carp, it provides energy when oxygen is scarce (along with lactic acid fermentation).
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Before fermentation, a glucose molecule breaks down into two pyruvate molecules (glycolysis).
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The energy from this exothermic reaction is used to bind inorganic phosphates to ADP, which converts it to ATP, and convert NAD+ to NADH.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The pyruvates break down into two acetaldehyde molecules and give off two carbon dioxide molecules as waste products.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The acetaldehyde is reduced into ethanol using the energy and hydrogen from NADH, and the NADH is oxidized into NAD+ so that the cycle may repeat.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The reaction is catalyzed by the enzymes pyruvate decarboxylase and alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The history of ethanol as a fuel spans several centuries and is marked by a series of significant milestones.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Samuel Morey, an American inventor, was the first to produce ethanol by fermenting corn in 1826.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] However, it was not until the California Gold Rush in the 1850s that ethanol was first used as a fuel in the United States.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Rudolf Diesel demonstrated his engine, which could run on vegetable oils and ethanol, in 1895, but the widespread use of petroleum-based diesel engines made ethanol less popular as a fuel.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In the 1970s, the oil crisis reignited interest in ethanol, and Brazil became a leader in ethanol production and use.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The United States began producing ethanol on a large scale in the 1980s and 1990s as a fuel additive to gasoline, due to government regulations.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Today, ethanol continues to be explored as a sustainable and renewable fuel source, with researchers developing new technologies and biomass sources for its production.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Pyruvate is the terminal electron acceptor in lactic acid fermentation, and *homolactic fermentation* (producing only lactic acid) is the simplest type of fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Pyruvate from glycolysis undergoes a simple redox reaction, forming lactic acid.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] It occurs in the muscles of animals when they need energy faster than the blood can supply oxygen.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] (In mammals, lactate can be transformed by the liver back into glucose using the Cori cycle.) It also occurs in some kinds of bacteria (such as lactobacilli) and some fungi.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] It is the type of bacteria that convert lactose into lactic acid in yogurt, giving it its sour taste.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Heterolactic fermentation is in a sense intermediate between lactic acid fermentation and other types, e.g. alcoholic fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Hydrogen gas is produced in many types of fermentation as a way to regenerate NAD+ from NADH.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Electrons are transferred to ferredoxin, which in turn is oxidized by hydrogenase, producing H2.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Hydrogen gas is a substrate for methanogens and sulfate reducers, which keep the concentration of hydrogen low and favor the production of such an energy-rich compound, but hydrogen gas at a fairly high concentration can nevertheless be formed, as in flatus.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] For example, *Clostridium pasteurianum* ferments glucose to butyrate, acetate, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen gas.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Glyoxylate fermentation is a type of fermentation used by microbes that are able to utilize glyoxylate as a nitrogen source.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Other types of fermentation include mixed acid fermentation, butanediol fermentation, butyrate fermentation, caproate fermentation, and acetone–butanol–ethanol fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In food and industrial contexts, any chemical modification performed by a living being in a controlled container can be termed "fermentation".
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Fermentation can be used to make alternative protein sources.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] It is commonly used to modify existing protein foods, including plant-based ones such as soy, into more flavorful forms such as tempeh and fermented tofu.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] More modern "fermentation" makes recombinant protein to help produce meat analogue, milk substitute, cheese analogues, and egg substitutes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Heme proteins such as myoglobin and hemoglobin give meat its characteristic texture, flavor, color, and aroma.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The myoglobin and leghemoglobin ingredients can be used to replicate this property, despite them coming from a vat instead of meat.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Industrial fermentation can be used for enzyme production, where proteins with catalytic activity are produced and secreted by microorganisms.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The development of fermentation processes, microbial strain engineering and recombinant gene technologies has enabled the commercialization of a wide range of enzymes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Enzymes are used in all kinds of industrial segments, such as food (lactose removal, cheese flavor), beverage (juice treatment), baking (bread softness, dough conditioning), animal feed, detergents (protein, starch and lipid stain removal), textile, personal care and pulp and paper industries.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Most industrial fermentation uses batch or fed-batch procedures, although continuous fermentation can be more economical if various challenges, particularly the difficulty of maintaining sterility, can be met.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In a batch process, all the ingredients are combined and the reactions proceed without any further input.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Batch fermentation has been used for millennia to make bread and alcoholic beverages, and it is still a common method, especially when the process is not well understood.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] However, it can be expensive because the fermentor must be sterilized using high pressure steam between batches.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Strictly speaking, there is often addition of small quantities of chemicals to control the pH or suppress foaming.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Batch fermentation goes through a series of phases.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] There is a lag phase in which cells adjust to their environment; then a phase in which exponential growth occurs.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Once many of the nutrients have been consumed, the growth slows and becomes non-exponential, but production of *secondary metabolites* (including commercially important antibiotics and enzymes) accelerates.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] This continues through a stationary phase after most of the nutrients have been consumed, and then the cells die.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Fed-batch fermentation is a variation of batch fermentation where some of the ingredients are added during the fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] This allows greater control over the stages of the process.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In particular, production of secondary metabolites can be increased by adding a limited quantity of nutrients during the non-exponential growth phase.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Fed-batch operations are often sandwiched between batch operations.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The high cost of sterilizing the fermentor between batches can be avoided using various open fermentation approaches that are able to resist contamination.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] One is to use a naturally evolved mixed culture.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] This is particularly favored in wastewater treatment, since mixed populations can adapt to a wide variety of wastes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Thermophilic bacteria can produce lactic acid at temperatures of around 50 °Celsius, sufficient to discourage microbial contamination; and ethanol has been produced at a temperature of 70 °C.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] This is just below its boiling point (78 °C), making it easy to extract.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Halophilic bacteria can produce bioplastics in hypersaline conditions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Solid-state fermentation adds a small amount of water to a solid substrate; it is widely used in the food industry to produce flavors, enzymes and organic acids.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In continuous fermentation, substrates are added and final products removed continuously.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] There are three varieties: chemostats, which hold nutrient levels constant; turbidostats, which keep cell mass constant; and plug flow reactors in which the culture medium flows steadily through a tube while the cells are recycled from the outlet to the inlet.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] If the process works well, there is a steady flow of feed and effluent and the costs of repeatedly setting up a batch are avoided.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Also, it can prolong the exponential growth phase and avoid byproducts that inhibit the reactions by continuously removing them.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] However, it is difficult to maintain a steady state and avoid contamination, and the design tends to be complex.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Typically the fermentor must run for over 500 hours to be more economical than batch processors.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Fermented foods have a religious significance in Judaism and Christianity.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The Baltic god Rugutis was worshiped as the agent of fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The 'father of modern chemistry', Antoine Lavoisier, had viewed fermentation as a simple chemical reaction and rejected the notion that living organisms could be involved.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] By the 19th century, this was seen as vitalism, which was lampooned in an anonymous 1839 publication by Justus von Liebig and Friedrich Wöhler.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In 1837, Charles Cagniard de la Tour, Theodor Schwann and Friedrich Traugott Kützing independently published papers concluding, as a result of microscopic investigations, that yeast is a living organism that reproduces by budding.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Schwann boiled grape juice to kill the yeast and found that no fermentation would occur until new yeast was added.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The turning point came when Louis Pasteur (1822–1895), during the 1850s and 1860s, repeated Schwann's experiments and showed fermentation is initiated by living organisms in a series of investigations.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In 1857, Pasteur showed lactic acid fermentation is caused by living organisms.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In 1860, he demonstrated how bacteria cause souring in milk, a process formerly thought to be merely a chemical change.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] His work in identifying the role of microorganisms in food spoilage led to the process of pasteurization.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In 1877, working to improve the French brewing industry, Pasteur published his famous paper on fermentation, "*Etudes sur la Bière*", which was translated into English in 1879 as "Studies on fermentation".
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] He defined fermentation (incorrectly) as "Life without air".
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Although showing fermentation resulted from the action of living microorganisms was a breakthrough, it did not explain the basic nature of fermentation; nor did it prove it is caused by microorganisms which appear to be always present.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Many scientists, including Pasteur, had unsuccessfully attempted to extract the fermentation enzyme from yeast.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Success came in 1897 when the German chemist Eduard Buechner ground up yeast, extracted a juice from them, then found to his amazement this "dead" liquid would ferment a sugar solution, forming carbon dioxide and alcohol much like living yeasts.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Buechner's results are considered to mark the birth of biochemistry.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The "unorganized ferments" behaved just like the organized ones.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] From that time on, the term enzyme came to be applied to all ferments.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] It was then understood fermentation is caused by enzymes produced by microorganisms.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In 1907, Buechner won the Nobel Prize in chemistry for his work.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Advances in microbiology and fermentation technology have continued steadily up until the present.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] For example, in the 1930s, it was discovered microorganisms could be mutated with physical and chemical treatments to be higher-yielding, faster-growing, tolerant of less oxygen, and able to use a more concentrated medium.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The field of fermentation has been critical to producing a wide range of consumer goods, from food and drink to industrial chemicals and pharmaceuticals.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Since its early beginnings in ancient civilizations, fermentation has continued to evolve and expand, with new techniques and technologies driving advances in product quality, yield, and efficiency.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In the 1970s and 1980s, fermentation became increasingly important in producing bulk chemicals like ethanol, lactic acid, and citric acid.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] This led to developing new fermentation techniques and genetically engineered microorganisms to improve yields and reduce production costs.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In the 1990s and 2000s, there was a growing interest in fermentation to produce functional foods and nutraceuticals, which have potential health benefits beyond basic nutrition.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] This led to new fermentation processes, probiotics, and other functional ingredients.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Recent research has begun to investigate the relationship between fermentation and creating a circular economy in effort to address the current climate crisis and the increasing demands for resources as the population grows.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The production of fuels, materials, and other chemicals has led to a notable increase in greenhouse gasses and a subsequent increase in global temperatures.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The current, linear economy relies heavily on fossil fuels and nonrenewable energy to produce chemicals and materials.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] In a circular economy, the use of renewable resources would be employed to produce chemicals; moreover, this type of economy focuses on reusing end-of-life chemicals and materials.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Investigation into alternative biofuels and biomaterials has become increasingly popular with fermentation as a notable method.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The primary source of biomass for fermentation is using biomass feedstocks which contain a mix of carbohydrates, proteins, oils and fats, and lignin.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Carbohydrates such as sucrose and starch (sources include sugarcane, corn, and cassava) are the most commonly used substrate for fermentation; however, in the discussion of biofuels, there are concerns regarding land competition between food and fuel biomass.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Attention has been turned towards second-generation biomass feedstock such as silvergrass or wood chips.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Anerobic digestion is found in all facets of biomass fermentation to create biofuels, biobased materials, and biochemicals.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] One of the most popular and established anaerobic fermentation process is the transformation of organic waste into biogas.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Further research has explored the possibility and reusing residual solids left over from fermentative processes and converting them into "char-based materials".
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] If successful, this would promote increased efficiency and a decreased environmental impact in the biomanufacturing industry.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Additionally, homogenous gas streams of CO2, and CH4, can be formed from anaerobic digestion by some bacteria, while other bacteria are able to fixate CO2 or CO and convert them into alcohols or fatty acids.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] One the most widely known biobased chemicals produced through fermentation, the process of fermenting sugars from plants into ethanol and CO2 uses *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Biobased ethanol is used as a popular renewable transportation fuel and also holds value in the chemical industry as the precursor for ethylene, which can be converted into polyethylene.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Commercial bioethanol production via fermentation is dominant in Brazil and the USA and employs sugarcane and starch from corn as feedstocks.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The process involves starch enzymatic hydrolysis to glucose, followed by fermentation and distillation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] There were around 200 ethanol plants operating in the U.S. as of 2021, with capacities of production varying from 6 kilotonnes to over one million tonnes annually.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Succinic acid is an important biobased chemical utilized for the production of biodegradable polymers including polybutylene succinate (PBS) and as feedstock to other biobased chemicals like 1,4-butanediol.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Succinic acid can be produced via the fermentation of sugar and carbon dioxide using native strains of bacteria; however, yields depend upon strain and conditions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Neutral or acidic fermentations are feasible, with low-pH fermentations facilitated by acid-resistant yeast strains simplifying downstream recovery through avoiding neutralization and reacidification.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Throughout the 2010s, several companies ordered commercial-scale production facilities, e.g., BioAmber, Myriant, Reverdia, and Succinity, on different host organisms and feedstocks like corn syrup and sorghum starch.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] While having proven the technical feasibility of succinic acid large-scale biobased production, most of them failed to compete economically with petrochemical products on a commercial scale.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Several of the plants were spun off or shut down to new proprietors, demonstrating the financial challenges of scaling up bio-based platforms within current markets.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] However, these projects are evidence that under right market conditions, succinic acid biobased has promise for greater industrial use.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Fermentation plays a significant role in producing precursor polymers to products and food additives such as amino acids, organic acids, triglycerides and fatty acids.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Amino acids are industrially produced through fermentation by microorganisms such as *Corynebacterium glutamicum* and *Escherichia coli*.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The global market application for amino acids is primarily food and feed additive.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] L-glutamic acid and L-lysine are the most commonly found amino acids in this market with L-glutamic acid being mainly used as a food flavoring in the form of monosodium glutamate (MSG) and L-lysine being mainly used as an animal feed supplement.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Other amino acids like L-threonine and L-phenylalanine are also produced on large scales for different applications.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Organic acids such as citric acid, lactic acid, and acetic acid are procured by microbial fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Citric acid finds widespread use in the food industry as a preservative and flavoring agent.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Lactic acid is used in food preservation and as a precursor for biodegradable plastics.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Acetic acid is used in food as vinegar and as a chemical reagent in industries.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] These organic acids are produced using microorganisms like *Aspergillus niger* and *Lactobacillus* species under controlled fermentation conditions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Fatty acids and triglycerides are produced by fermentation on oleaginous microorganisms such as *Yarrowia lipolytica* and certain fungi.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] These microorganisms can accumulate lipids under specific culture conditions and therefore are suitable for industrial-scale production of lipids.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The fatty acids produced can be used in the manufacture of soaps, detergents, and as starting compounds for various chemicals.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] Triglycerides are energy storage compounds with applications in the food industry and biofuel sector.
[src:metabolic-engineering/fermentation] The fermentation processes involve the optimization of environmental conditions and nutrient composition for maximum lipid accumulation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] In biochemistry and systems biology, **flux balance analysis** (**FBA**) is a mathematical method for simulating the metabolism of cells or entire unicellular organisms, such as *E. coli* or yeast, using genome-scale reconstructions of metabolic networks.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Genome-scale reconstructions describe all known or hypothesized biochemical reactions in an organism based on its entire genome.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] These reconstructions model metabolism by focusing on the interconversions between metabolites, identifying which metabolites are involved in the various reactions taking place in a cell or organism, and determining the genes that encode the enzymes which catalyze these reactions (if any).
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Earliest work in FBA dates back to the early 1980s.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Papoutsakis demonstrated that it was possible to construct flux balance equations using a metabolic map.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] It was Watson, however, who first introduced the idea of using linear programming and an objective function to solve for the fluxes in a pathway.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The first significant study was subsequently published by Fell and Small in 1986, who used flux balance analysis together with more elaborate objective functions to study the constraints in fat synthesis.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] FBA finds applications in bioprocess engineering to systematically identify modifications to the metabolic networks of microbes used in fermentation processes that improve product yields of industrially important chemicals such as ethanol and succinic acid.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] It has also been used for the identification of putative drug targets in cancer and pathogens, rational design of culture media, and host–pathogen interactions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The results of FBA can be visualized for smaller networks using flux maps similar to the image on the right, which illustrates the steady-state fluxes carried by reactions in glycolysis.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The thickness of the arrows is proportional to the flux through the reaction.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] In comparison to traditional methods of modeling, FBA is less intensive in terms of the input data required for constructing the model.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Simulations performed using FBA are computationally inexpensive and can calculate steady-state metabolic fluxes for large models (over 10,000 reactions) in a few seconds on modern personal computers.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] This means that the effect of deleting reactions from the network and/or changing flux constraints can be sensibly modelled on a single computer.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] A frequently used technique to search a metabolic network for reactions that are particularly critical to the production of biomass.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Pairwise reaction deletion of all possible pairs of reactions is useful when looking for drug targets, as it allows the simulation of multi-target treatments, either by a single drug with multiple targets or by drug combinations.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Double deletion studies can also quantify the synthetic lethal interactions between different pathways providing a measure of the contribution of the pathway to overall network robustness.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Genes are connected to enzyme-catalyzed reactions by Boolean expressions known as Gene-Protein-Reaction expressions (GPR).
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Typically a GPR takes the form (Gene A AND Gene B) to indicate that the products of genes A and B are protein sub-units that assemble to form the complete protein and therefore the absence of either would result in deletion of the reaction.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] On the other hand, if the GPR is (Gene A OR Gene B) it implies that the products of genes A and B are isozymes, meaning that the expression of either one is sufficient to maintain an active reaction.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] A reaction can also be regulated by a single gene, or in the case of diffusion, it may not be associated with any gene at all.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Therefore, it is possible to evaluate the effect of single or multiple gene deletions by evaluation of the GPR as a Boolean expression.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] If the GPR evaluates to **false**, the reaction is constrained to zero in the model prior to performing FBA.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Thus gene knockouts can be simulated using FBA.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Logically, reactions that are not associated with any genes cannot be deleted.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The utility of reaction inhibition and deletion analyses becomes most apparent if a gene-protein-reaction matrix has been assembled for the network being studied with FBA.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The gene-protein-reaction matrix is a binary matrix connecting genes with the proteins made from them.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Using this matrix, reaction essentiality can be converted into gene essentiality indicating the gene defects which may cause a certain disease phenotype or the proteins/enzymes which are essential (and thus what enzymes are the most promising drug targets in pathogens).
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] However, the gene-protein-reaction matrix does not specify the Boolean relationship between genes with respect to the enzyme, instead it merely indicates an association between them.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Therefore, it should be used only if the Boolean GPR expression is unavailable.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The effect of inhibiting a reaction, rather than removing it entirely, can be simulated in FBA by restricting the allowed flux through it.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The effect of an inhibition can be classified as lethal or non-lethal by applying the same criteria as in the case of a deletion where a suitable threshold is used to distinguish "substantially reduced" from "slightly reduced".
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Generally the choice of threshold is arbitrary but a reasonable estimate can be obtained from growth experiments where the simulated inhibitions/deletions are actually performed and growth rate is measured.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] To design optimal growth media with respect to enhanced growth rates or useful by-product secretion, it is possible to use a method known as Phenotypic Phase Plane analysis.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] PhPP involves applying FBA repeatedly on the model while co-varying the nutrient uptake constraints and observing the value of the objective function (or by-product fluxes).
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] PhPP makes it possible to find the optimal combination of nutrients that favor a particular phenotype or a mode of metabolism resulting in higher growth rates or secretion of industrially useful by-products.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The predicted growth rates of bacteria in varying media have been shown to correlate well with experimental results, as well as to define precise minimal media for the culture of *Salmonella typhimurium*.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The human microbiota is a complex system with as many as 400 trillion microbes and bacteria interacting with each other and the host.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] To understand key factors in this system; a multi-scale, dynamic flux-balance analysis is proposed as FBA is classified as less computationally intensive.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] FBA formalizes the system of equations describing the concentration changes in a metabolic network as the dot product of a matrix of the stoichiometric coefficients (the stoichiometric matrix **S**) and the vector **v** of the unsolved fluxes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The right-hand side of the dot product is a vector of zeros representing the system at steady state.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] At steady state, metabolite concentrations remain constant as the rates of production and consumption are balanced, resulting in no net change over time.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Since the system of equations is often underdetermined, there can be multiple possible solutions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] To obtain a single solution, the flux that maximizes a reaction of interest, such as biomass or ATP production, is selected.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Linear programming is then used to calculate one of the possible solutions of fluxes corresponding to the steady state.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] In contrast to the traditionally followed approach of metabolic modeling using coupled ordinary differential equations, flux balance analysis requires very little information in terms of the enzyme kinetic parameters and concentration of metabolites in the system.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] It achieves this by making two assumptions, steady state and optimality.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The first assumption is that the modeled system has entered a steady state, where the metabolite concentrations no longer change, i.e. in each metabolite node the producing and consuming fluxes cancel each other out.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The second assumption is that the organism has been optimized through evolution for some biological goal, such as optimal growth or conservation of resources.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The steady-state assumption dates to the ideas of material balance developed to model the growth of microbial cells in fermenters in bioprocess engineering.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] During microbial growth, a substrate consisting of a complex mixture of carbon, hydrogen, oxygen and nitrogen sources along with trace elements are consumed to generate biomass.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] If we consider the system of microbial cells to be at steady state then we may set the accumulation term to zero and reduce the material balance equations to simple algebraic equations.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] In such a system, substrate becomes the input to the system which is consumed and biomass is produced becoming the output from the system.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Mathematically, the algebraic equations can be represented as a dot product of a matrix of coefficients and a vector of the unknowns.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Since the steady-state assumption puts the accumulation term to zero.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Extending this idea to metabolic networks, it is possible to represent a metabolic network as a stoichiometry balanced set of equations.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Moving to the matrix formalism, we can represent the equations as the dot product of a matrix of stoichiometry coefficients (stoichiometric matrix S ) and the vector of fluxes $\mathbf {v}$ as the unknowns and set the right hand side to 0 implying the steady state.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Metabolic networks typically have more reactions than metabolites and this gives an under-determined system of linear equations containing more variables than equations.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The standard approach to solve such under-determined systems is to apply linear programming.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] where **x** represents the vector of variables (to be determined), **c** and **b** are vectors of (known) coefficients, *A* is a (known) matrix of coefficients, and $(\cdot )^{\mathrm {T} }$ is the matrix transpose.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The expression to be maximized or minimized is called the *objective function* (**c**T**x** in this case).
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The inequalities *A***x** ≤ **b** are the constraints which specify a convex polytope over which the objective function is to be optimized.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Linear Programming requires the definition of an objective function.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The optimal solution to the LP problem is considered to be the solution which maximizes or minimizes the value of the objective function depending on the case in point.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] In the case of flux balance analysis, the objective function **Z** for the LP is often defined as biomass production.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Biomass production is simulated by an equation representing a lumped reaction that converts various biomass precursors into one unit of biomass.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] where $\mathbf {v}$ represents the vector of fluxes (to be determined), S is a (known) matrix of coefficients.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The expression to be maximized or minimized is called the *objective function* ( $\mathbf {c} ^{\mathrm {T} }\mathbf {v}$ in this case).
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The inequalities $\mathbf {lowerbound} \leq \mathbf {v}$ and $\mathbf {v} \leq \mathbf {upperbound}$ define, respectively, the minimal and the maximal rates of flux for every reaction corresponding to the columns of the S matrix.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] These rates can be experimentally determined to constrain and improve the predictive accuracy of the model even further or they can be specified to an arbitrarily high value indicating no constraint on the flux through the reaction.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The stoichiometric coefficients alone are sufficient for the mathematical maximization of a specific objective function.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The objective function is essentially a measure of how each component in the system contributes to the production of the desired product.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The product itself depends on the purpose of the model, but one of the most common examples is the study of total biomass.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] A notable example of the success of FBA is the ability to accurately predict the growth rate of the prokaryote *E. coli* when cultured in different conditions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] In this case, the metabolic system was optimized to maximize the biomass objective function.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] However this model can be used to optimize the production of any product, and is often used to determine the output level of some biotechnologically relevant product.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The model itself can be experimentally verified by cultivating organisms using a chemostat or similar tools to ensure that nutrient concentrations are held constant.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Measurements of the production of the desired objective can then be used to correct the model.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The key parts of model preparation are: creating a metabolic network without gaps, adding constraints to the model, and finally adding an objective function (often called the Biomass function), usually to simulate the growth of the organism being modelled.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Metabolic networks can vary in scope from those describing a single pathway to those describing cell, tissue, or organism.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The main requirement of a metabolic network that forms the basis of an FBA-ready network is that it contains no gaps and correctly accounts for mass and charge balances of all biochemical processes therein.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] This typically means that extensive manual curation is required, making the preparation of a metabolic network for flux-balance analysis a process that can take months or years.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] However, recent advances, such as so-called gap-filling or mass-and-charge correction methods, can reduce the required time to weeks or months.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Software packages for creation of FBA models include: Pathway Tools/MetaFlux, Simpheny, MetNetMaker, COBRApy, CarveMe, MIOM, or COBREXA.jl.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Generally models are created in BioPAX, SBML, or Json format so that further analysis or visualization can take place in other software although this is not a requirement.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] A key part of FBA is the ability to add constraints to the flux rates of reactions within networks, forcing them to stay within a range of selected values.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] This lets the model more accurately simulate real metabolism.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The constraints belong to two subsets from a biological perspective; boundary constraints that limit nutrient uptake/excretion and internal constraints that limit the flux through reactions within the organism.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] In mathematical terms, the application of constraints can be considered to reduce the solution space of the FBA model.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] In addition to constraints applied at the edges of a metabolic network, constraints can be applied to reactions deep within the network.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] These constraints are usually simple; they may constrain the direction of a reaction due to energy considerations or constrain the maximum speed of a reaction due to the finite speed of all reactions in nature.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Organisms, and all other metabolic systems, require some input of nutrients.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] If the rate of absorption (and/or excretion) of certain nutrients can be experimentally measured then this information can be added as a constraint on the flux rate at the edges of a metabolic model.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] This ensures that nutrients that are not present or not absorbed by the organism do not enter its metabolism (the flux rate is constrained to zero) and also means that known nutrient uptake rates are adhered to by the simulation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] This provides a secondary method of making sure that the simulated metabolism has experimentally verified properties rather than just mathematically acceptable ones.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] In principle, all reactions are reversible however in practice reactions often effectively occur in only one direction.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] This may be due to significantly higher concentration of reactants compared to the concentration of the products of the reaction.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] But more often it happens because the products of a reaction have a much lower free energy than the reactants and therefore the forward direction of a reaction is favored more.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Certain flux rates can be measured experimentally ( $v_{i,m}\,$ ) and the fluxes within a metabolic model can be constrained, within some error ( $\varepsilon \,$ ), to ensure these known flux rates are accurately reproduced in the simulation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Flux rates are most easily measured for nutrient uptake at the edge of the network.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Measurements of internal fluxes is possible using radioactively labelled or NMR visible metabolites.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Constrained FBA-ready metabolic models can be analyzed using software such as the COBRA toolbox (available implementations in MATLAB and Python), SurreyFBA, or the web-based FAME.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Additional software packages have been listed elsewhere.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] A comprehensive review of all such software and their functionalities has been recently reviewed.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] An open-source alternative is available in the R (programming language) as the packages abcdeFBA or sybil for performing FBA and other constraint based modeling techniques.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] FBA can give a large number of mathematically acceptable solutions to the steady-state problem $(S{\vec {v}}=0)$ .
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] However solutions of biological interest are the ones which produce the desired metabolites in the correct proportion.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The objective function defines the proportion of these metabolites.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] For instance when modelling the growth of an organism the objective function is generally defined as biomass.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Mathematically, it is a column in the stoichiometry matrix the entries of which place a "demand" or act as a "sink" for biosynthetic precursors such as fatty acids, amino acids and cell wall components which are present on the corresponding rows of the **S** matrix.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] These entries represent experimentally measured, dry weight proportions of cellular components.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Therefore, this column becomes a lumped reaction that simulates growth and reproduction.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Therefore, the accuracy of experimental measurements plays an essential role in the correct definition of the biomass function and makes the results of FBA biologically applicable by ensuring that the correct proportion of metabolites are produced by metabolism.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] When modeling smaller networks the objective function can be changed accordingly.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] An example of this would be in the study of the carbohydrate metabolism pathways where the objective function would probably be defined as a certain proportion of ATP and NADH and thus simulate the production of high energy metabolites by this pathway.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Linear programming can be used to find a single optimal solution.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] In the more general case any reaction can be defined and added to the biomass function with either the condition that it be maximised or minimised if a single "optimal" solution is desired.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] In the case of there being only a single separate biomass function/reaction within the stoichiometric matrix ${\vec {c}}$ would simplify to all zeroes with a value of 1 (or any non-zero value) in the position corresponding to that biomass function.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Where there were multiple separate objective functions ${\vec {c}}$ would simplify to all zeroes with weighted values in the positions corresponding to all objective functions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The analysis of the null space of matrices is implemented in software packages specialized for matrix operations such as Matlab and Octave.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Determination of the null space of $\scriptstyle \mathbf {S}$ tells us all the possible collections of flux vectors (or linear combinations thereof) that balance fluxes within the biological network.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The advantage of this approach becomes evident in biological systems which are described by differential equation systems with many unknowns.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The velocities in the differential equations above — $v_{1}$ and $v_{2}$ — are dependent on the reaction rates of the underlying equations.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The velocities are generally taken from the Michaelis–Menten kinetic theory, which involves the kinetic parameters of the enzymes catalyzing the reactions and the concentration of the metabolites themselves.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Isolating enzymes from living organisms and measuring their kinetic parameters is a difficult task, as is measuring the internal concentrations and diffusion constants of metabolites within an organism.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Therefore, the differential equation approach to metabolic modeling is beyond the current scope of science for all but the most studied organisms.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] FBA avoids this impediment by applying the homeostatic assumption, which is a reasonably approximate description of biological systems.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Although FBA avoids that biological obstacle, the mathematical issue of a large solution space remains.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Accurately representing the biological limits of the system and returning the flux distribution closest to the natural fluxes within the target system/organism.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Certain biological principles can help overcome the mathematical difficulties.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The success of FBA and the realization of its limitations has led to extensions that attempt to mediate the limitations of the technique.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The optimal solution to the flux-balance problem is rarely unique with many possible, and equally optimal, solutions existing.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Flux variability analysis (FVA), built into some analysis software, returns the boundaries for the fluxes through each reaction that can, paired with the right combination of other fluxes, estimate the optimal solution.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Reactions which can support a low variability of fluxes through them are likely to be of a higher importance to an organism and FVA is a promising technique for the identification of reactions that are important.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] When simulating knockouts or growth on media, FBA gives the final steady-state flux distribution.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] This final steady state is reached in varying time-scales.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] For example, the predicted growth rate of *E. coli* on glycerol as the primary carbon source did not match the FBA predictions; however, on sub-culturing for 40 days or 700 generations, the growth rate adaptively evolved to match the FBA prediction.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Sometimes it is of interest to find out what is the immediate effect of a perturbation or knockout, since it takes time for regulatory changes to occur and for the organism to re-organize fluxes to optimally utilize a different carbon source or circumvent the effect of the knockout.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] MOMA predicts the immediate sub-optimal flux distribution following the perturbation by minimizing the distance (Euclidean) between the wild-type FBA flux distribution and the mutant flux distribution using quadratic programming.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] This yields an optimization problem of the form.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] where $\mathbf {v_{w}}$ represents the wild-type (or unperturbed state) flux distribution and $\mathbf {v_{d}}$ represents the flux distribution on gene deletion that is to be solved for.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] This is the MOMA solution which represents the flux distribution immediately post-perturbation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] ROOM attempts to improve the prediction of the metabolic state of an organism after a gene knockout.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] It follows the same premise as MOMA that an organism would try to restore a flux distribution as close as possible to the wild-type after a knockout.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] However it further hypothesizes that this steady state would be reached through a series of transient metabolic changes by the regulatory network and that the organism would try to minimize the number of regulatory changes required to reach the wild-type state.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Instead of using a distance metric minimization however it uses a mixed integer linear programming method.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Dynamic FBA attempts to add the ability for models to change over time, thus in some ways avoiding the strict steady state condition of pure FBA.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Typically the technique involves running an FBA simulation, changing the model based on the outputs of that simulation, and rerunning the simulation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] By repeating this process an element of feedback is achieved over time.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] FBA provides a less simplistic analysis than choke point analysis while requiring far less information on reaction rates and a much less complete network reconstruction than a full dynamic simulation would require.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] In filling this niche, FBA has been shown to be a very useful technique for analysis of the metabolic capabilities of cellular systems.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] This means that network effects, such as chemical reactions in distant pathways affecting each other, can be reproduced in the model.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] The upside to the inability of choke point analysis to simulate network effects is that it considers each reaction within a network in isolation and thus can suggest important reactions in a network even if a network is highly fragmented and contains many gaps.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Unlike dynamic metabolic simulation, FBA assumes that the internal concentration of metabolites within a system stays constant over time and thus is unable to provide anything other than steady-state solutions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] It is unlikely that FBA could, for example, simulate the functioning of a nerve cell.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] Since the internal concentration of metabolites is not considered within a model, it is possible that an FBA solution could contain metabolites at a concentration too high to be biologically acceptable.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] This is a problem that dynamic metabolic simulations would probably avoid.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] One advantage of the simplicity of FBA over dynamic simulations is that they are far less computationally expensive, allowing the simulation of large numbers of perturbations to the network.
[src:metabolic-engineering/flux-balance-analysis] A second advantage is that the reconstructed model can be substantially simpler by avoiding the need to consider enzyme rates and the effect of complex interactions on enzyme kinetics.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The medical application to industrial microbiology is the production of new drugs synthesized in a specific organism for medical purposes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Production of antibiotics is necessary for the treatment of many bacterial infections.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Some natural occurring antibiotics and precursors, are produced through a process called fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The microorganisms grow in a liquid media where the population size is controlled in order to yield the greatest amount of product.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] In this environment nutrient, pH, temperature, and oxygen are controlled also in order to maximize the amount of cells and cause them not to die before the production of the antibiotic of interest.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Once the antibiotic is produced it must be extracted in order to yield an income.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Vitamins also get produced in massive quantities either by fermentation or biotransformation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Vitamin B 2 (riboflavin) for example is produced both ways.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Biotransformation is mostly used for the production of riboflavin, and the carbon source starting material for this reaction is glucose.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] There are a few strains of microorganisms that were engineered to increase the yield of riboflavin produced.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The most common organism used for this reaction is *Ashbya gossypii*.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The fermentation process is another common way to produce riboflavin.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The most common organism used for production of riboflavin through fermentation is *Eremothecium ashbyii*.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Once riboflavin is produced it must be extracted from the broth, this is done by heating the cells for a certain amount of time, and then the cells can be filtered out of solution.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Riboflavin is later purified and released as final product.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Microbial biotransformation can be used to produce steroid medicaments.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Steroids can be consumed either orally or by injection.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Steroids play a big role in the control of arthritis.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Cortisone is an anti-inflammatory drug that fights against arthritis, as well as several skin diseases.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Fermentation is a reaction where sugar can be converted into a gas, alcohols or acids.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Fermentation happens anaerobically, which means microorganisms that go through fermentation can function without the presence of oxygen.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Yeasts and bacteria are commonly used to mass produce multiple products.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Drinking alcohol is a product that is produced by yeasts and bacteria.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Alcohol that can be consumed is also known as ethanol, and ethanol is used to power automobiles as a fuel source.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Drinking alcohol is produced from natural sugars like glucose.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Carbon dioxide is produced as a side product in this reaction and can be used to make bread, and can also be used to carbonate beverages.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Fermentation Wine: Alcoholic beverages like beer and wine are fermented by microorganisms when there is no oxygen present.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] In this process, once there is enough alcohol and carbon dioxide around in the media the yeast start to die due to the environment becoming toxic to them.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] There are many strains of yeast and bacteria that can tolerate different amounts of alcohol around in their environment before it becoming toxic, thus one can obtain different alcohol levels in beer and wine, just by selecting a different microbial strain.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Most yeast can tolerate between 10 and 15 percent alcohol, but there are some strains that can tolerate up to 21 percent alcohol.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Dairy products like cheese and yogurt can also be made through fermentation using microbes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Cheese was produced as a way to preserve the nutrients obtained from milk, through fermentation thus elongating the shelf-life of the product.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Microbes are used to convert the lactose sugars into lactic acid through fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The bacteria used for such fermentation are usually from *Lactococci*, *Lactobacilli*, or *Streptococci* families.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Sometimes these microbes are added before or after the acidification step needed for cheese production.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Also these microbes are responsible for the different flavors of cheese, since they have enzymes that breakdown milk sugars and fats into multiple building blocks.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Some other microbes like mold may be purposely introduced during or before the aging of the cheese, in order to give it a different flavor.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The production of yogurt starts from the pasteurization of milk, where undesired microbes are reduced or eliminated.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Once the milk is pasteurized the milk is ready to be processed to reduce fat and liquid content, so what remains is mostly solid content.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] This can be done by drying the milk so that the liquid evaporates or by adding concentrated milk.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Increasing the solid content of the milk also increases the nutritional value since the nutrients are more concentrated.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] After this step is accomplished, the milk is ready for fermentation where the milk gets inoculated with bacteria in hygienic stainless steel containers and then gets carefully monitored for lactic acid production, temperature and pH.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Enzymes can be produced through fermentation either by submerged fermentation and/ or by solid state fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Submerged fermentation is referred to when the microorganisms are in contact with media.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] In this process the contact with oxygen is essential.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The bioreactors/fermentors that are used to do these mass production of product can store up to 500 cubic meters in volume.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Solid state fermentation is less common than submerged fermentation, but has many benefits.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] There is less need for the environment to be sterile since there is less water, there is a higher stability and concentration for the end product.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The demand for agricultural products is constantly increasing due to the need of various fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] There are long term effects of the overuse of chemical fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Due to the excessive use of chemical fertilizers and pesticides, the soil becomes infertile and a non-sufficient use for growing crops.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] For that matter, biofertelizers, biopesticides and organic farming come to the rescue.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Biopesticide is a pesticide derived from a living organism or natural occurring substances.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Biochemical pesticides can also be produced from naturally occurring substances that can control pest populations in a non-toxic matter.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] An example of a biochemical pesticide is garlic and pepper based insecticides, these work by repelling insects from the desired location.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Microbial pesticides, usually a virus, bacterium, or fungus are used to control pest populations in a more specific manner.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The most commonly used microbe for the production of microbial bio-pesticides is *Bacillus thuringiensis*, also known as Bt.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] This spore forming bacterium produces a delta-endotoxins in which it causes the insect or pest to stop feeding on the crop or plant because the endotoxin destroys the lining of the digestive system.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Synthesis of amino acids and organic solvents can also be made using microbes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The synthesis of essential amino acids such as are L-Methionine, L-Lysine, L-Tryptophan and the non-essential amino acid L-glutamic acid are used today mainly for feed, food, and pharmaceutical industries.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The production of these amino acids is due to *Corynebacterium glutamicum* and fermentation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] *C.glutamicum* was engineered to be able to produce L-lysine and L-Glutamic acid in large quantities.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] L-Glutamic acid had a high demand for production because this amino acid is used to produce Monosodium glutamate (MSG) a food flavoring agent.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] This organism and other autotrophs were later modified to yield other amino acids such as lysine, aspartate, methionine, isoleucine and threonine.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] L-Lysine is used for the feeding of pigs and chicken, as well as to treat nutrient deficiency, increase energy in a patient, and sometimes used to treat viral infections.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] L-Tryptophan is also produced through fermentation and by *Corynebacterium* and *E.coli,* though the production is not as large as the rest of the amino acids it is still produced for pharmaceutical purposes since it can be converted and used to produce neurotransmitters.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The production of organic solvents like acetone, butanol, and isopropanol through fermentation was one of the first things to be produced by using bacteria, since achieving the necessary chirality of the products is easily achieved by using living systems.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Solvent fermentation uses a series of *Clostridia* bacterial species.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Solvent fermentation at first was not as productive as it is used today.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] The amount of bacteria required to yield a product was high, and the actual yield of product was low.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Later technological advances were discovered that allowed scientist to genetically alter these strains to achieve a higher yield for these solvents.
[src:metabolic-engineering/industrial-microbiology] Yielding more strains that can use other substrates was also another way to increase the productivity of these bacteria.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] The ultimate goal of metabolic engineering is to be able to use these organisms to produce valuable substances on an industrial scale in a cost-effective manner.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Current examples include producing beer, wine, cheese, pharmaceuticals, and other biotechnology products.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Another possible area of use is the development of oil crops whose composition has been modified to improve their nutritional value.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Some of the common strategies used for metabolic engineering are (1) overexpressing the gene encoding the rate-limiting enzyme of the biosynthetic pathway, (2) blocking the competing metabolic pathways, (3) heterologous gene expression, and (4) enzyme engineering.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Since cells use these metabolic networks for their survival, changes can have drastic effects on the cells' viability.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Therefore, trade-offs in metabolic engineering arise between the cells ability to produce the desired substance and its natural survival needs.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Therefore, instead of directly deleting and/or overexpressing the genes that encode for metabolic enzymes, the current focus is to target the regulatory networks in a cell to efficiently engineer the metabolism.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] In the past, to increase the productivity of a desired metabolite, a microorganism was genetically modified by chemically induced mutation, and the mutant strain that overexpressed the desired metabolite was then chosen.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] However, one of the main problems with this technique was that the metabolic pathway for the production of that metabolite was not analyzed, and as a result, the constraints to production and relevant pathway enzymes to be modified were unknown.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] In 1990s, a new technique called metabolic engineering emerged.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] This technique analyzes the metabolic pathway of a microorganism, and determines the constraints and their effects on the production of desired compounds.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] It then uses genetic engineering to relieve these constraints.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] It was determined through metabolic flux analysis that the theoretical maximal yield of DAHP per glucose molecule utilized, was 3/7.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] This is because some of the carbon from glucose is lost as carbon dioxide, instead of being utilized to produce DAHP.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Also, one of the metabolites (PEP, or phosphoenolpyruvate) that are used to produce DAHP, was being converted to pyruvate (PYR) to transport glucose into the cell, and therefore, was no longer available to produce DAHP.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] In order to relieve the shortage of PEP and increase yield, Patnaik et al. used genetic engineering on *E. coli* to introduce a reaction that converts PYR back to PEP.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Thus, the PEP used to transport glucose into the cell is regenerated, and can be used to make DAHP.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] This resulted in a new theoretical maximal yield of 6/7 – double that of the native *E. coli* system.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] At the industrial scale, metabolic engineering is becoming more convenient and cost-effective.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] According to the Biotechnology Industry Organization, "more than 50 biorefinery facilities are being built across North America to apply metabolic engineering to produce biofuels and chemicals from renewable biomass which can help reduce greenhouse gas emissions".
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Potential biofuels include short-chain alcohols and alkanes (to replace gasoline), fatty acid methyl esters and fatty alcohols (to replace diesel), and fatty acid-and isoprenoid-based biofuels (to replace diesel).
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Metabolic engineering continues to evolve in efficiency and processes aided by breakthroughs in the field of synthetic biology and progress in understanding metabolite damage and its repair or preemption.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Early metabolic engineering experiments showed that accumulation of reactive intermediates can limit flux in engineered pathways and be deleterious to host cells if matching damage control systems are missing or inadequate.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Researchers in synthetic biology optimize genetic pathways, which in turn influence cellular metabolic outputs.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Recent decreases in cost of synthesized DNA and developments in genetic circuits help to influence the ability of metabolic engineering to produce desired outputs.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] The first step in the process is to identify a desired goal to achieve through the improvement or modification of an organism's metabolism.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Reference books and online databases are used to research reactions and metabolic pathways that are able to produce this product or result.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] These databases contain copious genomic and chemical information including pathways for metabolism and other cellular processes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Using this research, an organism is chosen that will be used to create the desired product or result.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Considerations that are taken into account when making this decision are how close the organism's metabolic pathway is to the desired pathway, the maintenance costs associated with the organism, and how easy it is to modify the pathway of the organism.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] *Escherichia coli* (*E. coli*) is widely used in metabolic engineering to synthesize a wide variety of products such as amino acids because it is relatively easy to maintain and modify.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] If the organism does not contain the complete pathway for the desired product or result, then genes that produce the missing enzymes must be incorporated into the organism.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] The completed metabolic pathway is modeled mathematically to find the theoretical yield of the product or the reaction fluxes in the cell.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] A flux is the rate at which a given reaction in the network occurs.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Simple metabolic pathway analysis can be done by hand, but most require the use of software to perform the computations.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] These programs use complex linear algebra algorithms to solve these models.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] To solve a network using the equation for determined systems shown below, one must input the necessary information about the relevant reactions and their fluxes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Information about the reaction (such as the reactants and stoichiometry) are contained in the matrices Gx and Gm.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Matrices Vm and Vx contain the fluxes of the relevant reactions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] When solved, the equation yields the values of all the unknown fluxes (contained in Vx).
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] After solving for the fluxes of reactions in the network, it is necessary to determine which reactions may be altered in order to maximize the yield of the desired product.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] To determine what specific genetic manipulations to perform, it is necessary to use computational algorithms, such as OptGene or OptFlux.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] They provide recommendations for which genes should be overexpressed, knocked out, or introduced in a cell to allow increased production of the desired product.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] For example, if a given reaction has particularly low flux and is limiting the amount of product, the software may recommend that the enzyme catalyzing this reaction should be overexpressed in the cell to increase the reaction flux.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] The necessary genetic manipulations can be performed using standard molecular biology techniques.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Genes may be overexpressed or knocked out from an organism, depending on their effect on the pathway and the ultimate goal.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] In order to create a solvable model, it is often necessary to have certain fluxes already known or experimentally measured.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] In addition, in order to verify the effect of genetic manipulations on the metabolic network (to ensure they align with the model), it is necessary to experimentally measure the fluxes in the network.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] To measure reaction fluxes, carbon flux measurements are made using carbon-13 isotopic labeling.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] The organism is fed a mixture that contains molecules where specific carbons are engineered to be carbon-13 atoms, instead of carbon-12.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] After these molecules are used in the network, downstream metabolites also become labeled with carbon-13, as they incorporate those atoms in their structures.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] The specific labeling pattern of the various metabolites is determined by the reaction fluxes in the network.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-engineering] Labeling patterns may be measured using techniques such as gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC-MS) along with computational algorithms to determine reaction fluxes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Metabolic flux analysis may use 13C-labeled isotope tracers for isotopic labeling experiments.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) techniques and mass spectrometry may then be used to measure metabolite labeling patterns to provide information for determination of pathway fluxes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Because MFA typically requires rigorous flux calculation of complex metabolic networks, publicly available software tools have been developed to automate MFA and reduce its computational burden.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Although using a stoichiometric balance and constraints of the metabolites comprising the metabolic network can elucidate fluxes, this approach has limitations including difficulty in stimulating fluxes through parallel, cyclic, and reversible pathways.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Moreover, there is limited insight on how metabolites interconvert in a metabolic network without the use of isotope tracers.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Thus, the use of isotopes has become the dominant technique for MFA.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Isotope labeling experiments are optimal for gathering experimental data necessary for MFA.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Because fluxes determine the isotopic labeling patterns of intracellular metabolites, measuring these patterns allows for inference of fluxes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] The first step in the workflow of isotope labeling experiments is cell culture on labeled substrates.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] A substrate such as glucose is labeled by isotope(s), most often 13C, and is introduced into the culture medium.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] The medium also typically contains vitamins and essential amino acids to facilitate cells' growth.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] The labeled substrate is then metabolized by the cells, leading to the incorporation of the 13C tracer in other intracellular metabolites.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] After the cells reach steady-state physiology (i.e., constant metabolite concentrations in culture), cells are then lysed to extract metabolites.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] For mammalian cells, extraction involves quenching of cells using methanol to stop their cellular metabolism and subsequent extraction of metabolites using methanol and water extraction.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Concentrations of metabolites and labeled isotope in metabolites of the extracts are measured by instruments like liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry or NMR, which also provide information on the position and number of labeled atoms on the metabolites.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] These data are necessary for gaining insight into the dynamics of intracellular metabolism and metabolite turnover rates to infer metabolic flux.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] A predominant method for metabolic flux analysis is isotopically stationary MFA.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] This technique for flux quantitation is applicable under metabolic and isotopic steady-state, two conditions that assume that metabolite concentrations and isotopomer distributions are not changing over time, respectively.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Knowledge of the stoichiometric matrix (S) comprising the consumption and production of metabolites within biochemical reactions is needed to balance fluxes (v) around the assumed metabolic network model.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] To reduce the possible solution space for flux distributions, isotopically stationary MFA requires additional stoichiometric constraints such as growth rates, substrate secretion and uptake, and product accumulation rates as well as upper and lower bounds for fluxes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Although isotopically stationary MFA allows precise deduction of metabolic fluxes through mathematical modeling, the analysis is limited to batch cultures during the exponential phase.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Moreover, after addition of a labeled substrate, the time-point for when metabolic and isotopic steady-state may be accurately assumed can be difficult to determine.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] When isotope labeling is transient and has not yet equilibrated, isotopically non-stationary MFA (INST-MFA) is advantageous in deducing fluxes, particularly for systems with slow labeling dynamics.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Similar to isotopically stationary MFA, this method requires mass and isotopomer balances to characterize the stoichiometry and atom transitions of the metabolic network.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] INST-MFA is thus a powerful method for elucidating fluxes of systems with pathway bottlenecks and revealing metabolic phenotypes of autotrophic organisms.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Although INST-MFA's computationally intensive demands previously hindered its widespread use, newly developed software tools have streamlined INST-MFA to decrease computational time and demand.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Thermodynamics-Based Metabolic Flux Analysis (TMFA) is a specialized type of metabolic flux analysis which utilizes linear thermodynamic constraints in addition to mass balance constraints to generate thermodynamically feasible fluxes and metabolite activity profiles.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] TMFA takes into consideration only pathways and fluxes that are feasible by using the Gibbs free energy change of the reactions and activities of the metabolites that are part of the model.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] By calculating Gibbs free energies of metabolic reactions and consequently their thermodynamic favorability, TMFA facilitates identification of limiting pathway bottleneck reactions that may be ideal candidates for pathway regulation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Simulation algorithms are needed to model the biological system and calculate the fluxes of all pathways in a complex network.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Several computational software exist to meet the need for efficient and precise tools for flux quantitation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Examples of MFA software include 13CFLUX2 and OpenFLUX, which evaluate 13C labeling experiments for flux calculation under metabolic and isotopically stationary conditions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] The increasing interest in developing computation tools for INST-MFA calculation has also led to the development of software applications such as INCA, which was the first software capable of performing INST-MFA and simulating transient isotope labeling experiments.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Metabolic flux analysis has been used to guide scale-up efforts for fermentation of biofuels.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] By directly measuring enzymatic reaction rates, MFA can capture the dynamics of cells' behavior and metabolic phenotypes in bioreactors during large-scale fermentations.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] For example, MFA models were used to optimize the conversion of xylose into ethanol in xylose-fermenting yeast by using calculated flux distributions to determine maximal theoretical capacities of the selected yeast towards ethanol production.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Identification of bottleneck enzymes determines rate-limiting reactions that limit the productivity of a biosynthetic pathway.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-flux-analysis] Moreover, MFA can help predict unexpected phenotypes of genetically engineered strains by constructing a fundamental understanding of how fluxes are wired in engineered cells.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] In biochemistry, a **metabolic pathway** is a linked series of chemical reactions occurring within a cell.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The reactants, products, and intermediates of an enzymatic reaction are known as metabolites, which are modified by a sequence of chemical reactions catalyzed by enzymes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] In most cases of a metabolic pathway, the product of one enzyme acts as the substrate for the next.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] However, side products are considered waste and removed from the cell.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Different metabolic pathways function in the position within a eukaryotic cell and the significance of the pathway in the given compartment of the cell.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] For instance, the electron transport chain and oxidative phosphorylation all take place in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] In contrast, glycolysis, pentose phosphate pathway, and fatty acid biosynthesis all occur in the cytosol of a cell.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] There are two types of metabolic pathways that are characterized by their ability to either synthesize molecules with the utilization of energy (anabolic pathway), or break down complex molecules and release energy in the process (catabolic pathway).
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The two pathways complement each other in that the energy released from one is used up by the other.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The degradative process of a catabolic pathway provides the energy required to conduct the biosynthesis of an anabolic pathway.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] In addition to the two distinct metabolic pathways is the amphibolic pathway, which can be either catabolic or anabolic based on the need for or the availability of energy.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Pathways are required for the maintenance of homeostasis within an organism and the flux of metabolites through a pathway is regulated depending on the needs of the cell and the availability of the substrate.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The end product of a pathway may be used immediately, initiate another metabolic pathway or be stored for later use.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The metabolism of a cell consists of an elaborate network of interconnected pathways that enable the synthesis and breakdown of molecules (anabolism and catabolism).
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Each metabolic pathway consists of a series of biochemical reactions that are connected by their intermediates: the products of one reaction are the substrates for subsequent reactions, and so on.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Metabolic pathways are often considered to flow in one direction.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Although all chemical reactions are technically reversible, conditions in the cell are often such that it is thermodynamically more favorable for flux to proceed in one direction of a reaction.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] For example, one pathway may be responsible for the synthesis of a particular amino acid, but the breakdown of that amino acid may occur via a separate and distinct pathway.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] One example of an exception to this "rule" is the metabolism of glucose.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Glycolysis results in the breakdown of glucose, but several reactions in the glycolysis pathway are reversible and participate in the re-synthesis of glucose (gluconeogenesis).
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] In times of excess lipid or protein energy sources, certain reactions in the glycolysis pathway may run in reverse to produce glucose 6-phosphate, which is then used for storage as glycogen or starch.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The net reaction is, therefore, thermodynamically favorable, for it results in a lower free energy for the final products.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] A catabolic pathway is an exergonic system that produces chemical energy in the form of ATP, GTP, NADH, NADPH, FADH2, etc. from energy containing sources such as carbohydrates, fats, and proteins.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The end products are often carbon dioxide, water, and ammonia.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Coupled with an endergonic reaction of anabolism, the cell can synthesize new macromolecules using the original precursors of the anabolic pathway.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] An example of a coupled reaction is the phosphorylation of fructose-6-phosphate to form the intermediate fructose-1,6-bisphosphate by the enzyme phosphofructokinase accompanied by the hydrolysis of ATP in the pathway of glycolysis.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The resulting chemical reaction within the metabolic pathway is highly thermodynamically favorable and, as a result, irreversible in the cell.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] A core set of energy-producing catabolic pathways occur within all living organisms in some form.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] These pathways transfer the energy released by breakdown of nutrients into ATP and other small molecules used for energy (e.g.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] All cells can perform anaerobic respiration by glycolysis.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Additionally, most organisms can perform more efficient aerobic respiration through the citric acid cycle and oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Additionally plants, algae and cyanobacteria are able to use sunlight to anabolically synthesize compounds from non-living matter by photosynthesis.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] In contrast to catabolic pathways, **anabolic pathways** require an energy input to construct macromolecules such as polypeptides, nucleic acids, proteins, polysaccharides, and lipids.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The isolated reaction of anabolism is unfavorable in a cell due to a positive Gibbs free energy (+Δ*G*).
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Thus, an input of chemical energy through a coupling with an exergonic reaction is necessary.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The coupled reaction of the catabolic pathway affects the thermodynamics of the reaction by lowering the overall activation energy of an anabolic pathway and allowing the reaction to take place.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Otherwise, an endergonic reaction is non-spontaneous.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] An anabolic pathway is a biosynthetic pathway, meaning that it combines smaller molecules to form larger and more complex ones.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] An example is the reversed pathway of glycolysis, otherwise known as gluconeogenesis, which occurs in the liver and sometimes in the kidney to maintain proper glucose concentration in the blood and supply the brain and muscle tissues with adequate amount of glucose.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Although gluconeogenesis is similar to the reverse pathway of glycolysis, it contains four distinct enzymes(pyruvate carboxylase, phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase, fructose 1,6-bisphosphatase, glucose 6-phosphatase) from glycolysis that allow the pathway to occur spontaneously.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] An **amphibolic pathway** is one that can be either catabolic or anabolic based on the availability of or the need for energy.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The currency of energy in a biological cell is adenosine triphosphate (ATP), which stores its energy in the phosphoanhydride bonds.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The energy is utilized to conduct biosynthesis, facilitate movement, and regulate active transport inside of the cell.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Examples of amphibolic pathways are the citric acid cycle and the glyoxylate cycle.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] These sets of chemical reactions contain both energy producing and utilizing pathways.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] To the right is an illustration of the amphibolic properties of the TCA cycle.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The glyoxylate shunt pathway is an alternative to the tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle, for it redirects the pathway of TCA to prevent full oxidation of carbon compounds, and to preserve high energy carbon sources as future energy sources.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] This pathway occurs only in plants and bacteria and transpires in the absence of glucose molecules.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The flux of the entire pathway is regulated by the rate-determining steps.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] These are the slowest steps in a network of reactions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The rate-limiting step occurs near the beginning of the pathway and is regulated by feedback inhibition, which ultimately controls the overall rate of the pathway.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The metabolic pathway in the cell is regulated by covalent or non-covalent modifications.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] A covalent modification involves an addition or removal of a chemical bond, whereas a non-covalent modification (also known as allosteric regulation) is the binding of the regulator to the enzyme via hydrogen bonds, electrostatic interactions, and Van der Waals forces.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The rate of turnover in a metabolic pathway, also known as the metabolic flux, is regulated based on the stoichiometric reaction model, the utilization rate of metabolites, and the translocation pace of molecules across the lipid bilayer.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The regulation methods are based on experiments involving 13C-labeling, which is then analyzed by nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) or gas chromatography–mass spectrometry (GC–MS)–derived mass compositions.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The aforementioned techniques synthesize a statistical interpretation of mass distribution in proteinogenic amino acids to the catalytic activities of enzymes in a cell.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Metabolic pathways can be targeted for clinically therapeutic uses.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Within the mitochondrial metabolic network, for instance, there are various pathways that can be targeted by compounds to prevent cancer cell proliferation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] One such pathway is oxidative phosphorylation (OXPHOS) within the electron transport chain (ETC).
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Various inhibitors can downregulate the electrochemical reactions that take place at Complex I, II, III, and IV, thereby preventing the formation of an electrochemical gradient and downregulating the movement of electrons through the ETC.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The substrate-level phosphorylation that occurs at ATP synthase can also be directly inhibited, preventing the formation of ATP that is necessary to supply energy for cancer cell proliferation.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Some of these inhibitors, such as lonidamine and atovaquone, which inhibit Complex II and Complex III, respectively, are currently undergoing clinical trials for FDA approval.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Other non-FDA-approved inhibitors have still shown experimental success in vitro.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Heme, an important prosthetic group present in Complexes I, II, and IV can also be targeted, since heme biosynthesis and uptake have been correlated with increased cancer progression.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Various molecules can inhibit heme via different mechanisms.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] For instance, succinylacetone has been shown to decrease heme concentrations by inhibiting δ-aminolevulinic acid in murine erythroleukemia cells.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The primary structure of heme-sequestering peptides, such as HSP1 and HSP2, can be modified to downregulate heme concentrations and reduce proliferation of non-small lung cancer cells.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The tricarboxylic acid cycle (TCA) and glutaminolysis can also be targeted for cancer treatment, since they are essential for the survival and proliferation of cancer cells.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Ivosidenib and enasidenib, two FDA-approved cancer treatments, can arrest the TCA cycle of cancer cells by inhibiting isocitrate dehydrogenase-1 (IDH1) and isocitrate dehydrogenase-2 (IDH2), respectively.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Ivosidenib is specific to acute myeloid leukemia (AML) and cholangiocarcinoma, whereas enasidenib is specific to just acute myeloid leukemia (AML).
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] In a clinical trial consisting of 185 adult patients with cholangiocarcinoma and an IDH-1 mutation, there was a statistically significant improvement (p<0.0001; HR: 0.37) in patients randomized to ivosidenib.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Still, some of the adverse side effects in these patients included fatigue, nausea, diarrhea, decreased appetite, ascites, and anemia.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] In a clinical trial consisting of 199 adult patients with AML and an IDH2 mutation, 23% of patients experienced complete response (CR) or complete response with partial hematologic recovery (CRh) lasting a median of 8.2 months while on enasidenib.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Of the 157 patients who required transfusion at the beginning of the trial, 34% no longer required transfusions during the 56-day time period on enasidenib.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Of the 42% of patients who did not require transfusions at the beginning of the trial, 76% still did not require a transfusion by the end of the trial.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Side effects of enasidenib included nausea, diarrhea, elevated bilirubin and, most notably, differentiation syndrome.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Glutaminase (GLS), the enzyme responsible for converting glutamine to glutamate via hydrolytic deamidation during the first reaction of glutaminolysis, can also be targeted.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] In recent years, many small molecules, such as azaserine, acivicin, and CB-839 have been shown to inhibit glutaminase, thus reducing cancer cell viability and inducing apoptosis in cancer cells.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Due to its effective antitumor ability in several cancer types such as ovarian, breast and lung cancers, CB-839 is the only GLS inhibitor currently undergoing clinical studies for FDA-approval.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] Many metabolic pathways are of commercial interest.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] For instance, the production of many antibiotics or other drugs requires complex pathways.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The pathways to produce such compounds can be transplanted into microbes or other more suitable organism for production purposes.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] For example, the world's supply of the anti-cancer drug vinblastine is produced by relatively ineffient extraction and purification of the precursors vindoline and catharanthine from the plant *Catharanthus roseus*, which are then chemically converted into vinblastine.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] The biosynthetic pathway to produce vinblastine, including 30 enzymatic steps, has been transferred into yeast cells which is a convenient system to grow in large amounts.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] With these genetic modifications yeast can use its own metabolites geranyl pyrophosphate and tryptophan to produce the precursors of catharanthine and vindoline.
[src:metabolic-engineering/metabolic-pathway] This process required 56 genetic edits, including expression of 34 heterologous genes from plants in yeast cells.
